        "content": "<p>In treating differential cohomology through the hexagon, one has several maps involving an object (a spectrum) and its image under different modalities like the flat modality or the shape modality. There is in particular the canonical map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{X} \\to \\mathrm{Sh}\\mathcal{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1464em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1464em;\">X</span></span></span></span> from the object to its shape. My question is, is there a concrete characterization of the cokernel of this map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{X} \\to \\mathrm{Sh}\\mathcal{X} \\to \\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1464em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1464em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0583em;\">C</span></span></span></span>? I am particularly interested in the unstable case, meaning smooth infinity groupoids, but there might be better luck with spectra.</p>",
        "id": 595875149,
        "sender_full_name": "Alonso Perez-Lona",
